In the light of the correlation, we suggest that the ULF waves are responsible for the periodicity of the EMIC-wave packets. As suggested by previous studies10–12, magnetospheric EMIC waves are usually generated by the ion cyclotron anisotropy (ICA) instability, in which hot anisotropic ions act as free energy sources. This is the case here. When interacting with the ULF waves, H+ ions are quasi-periodically accelerated, especially those in the energy range of 9.8–26.6 keV (Fig. 1b). As a result, their velocity distributions quasi-periodically become more dominated by perpendicular motion than field-aligned motion, or in short, become more anisotropic (Fig. 1g). These quasi-periodic anisotropy enhancements coincide with the EMIC-wave packets. A one-to-one correspondence can be identified between them, if one compares Fig. 1g, h. Further, we note that when EMIC waves appear, the 9.8–26.6 keV H+ ions are extracting energy from the ULF waves. Figure 1f shows the ion energy gain calculated from the observed ULF-wave electric fields (Ew,ULF\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
